    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-11T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-11T10:00:00-05:00" n="636"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d636">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/8961: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-11T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 11, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 12—9:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>135. My telegrams 131 of March 10, 2 p.m., and 134, March 11, 4 p.m. Johnson
                    informed Reed<note n="45" xml:id="d636fn45">Leslie E. Reed, First Secretary of
                        Legation in Greece.</note> this morning that he did not mean to imply
                    yesterday the presence of British troops in Salonika but only of a certain
                    number of civilians. The British Military Attaché refers to these as possible
                    “transients”.</p>
                <p>Department’s telegram No. 92<note n="46" xml:id="d636fn46">Dated March 10, not
                        printed.</note> received today.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
